queries.response:
The root cause of the stack buffer overflow is an off-by-one error in the `for` loop condition within the `crc8` function.

### Analysis of the Defect

In `program.c`, the `crc8` function is defined as:

```c
static uint8_t crc8(const uint8_t *buf, size_t len) {
    uint8_t crc = 0x00;
    // ...
    for (size_t i = 0; i <= len; i++) { // The error is here
        crc ^= buf[i];
        // ...
    }
    return crc;
}
```

The function receives `len`, which is the correct number of bytes in the input buffer `buf`. In C, array indexing is zero-based: if a buffer has size `len`, its valid elements range from `buf[0]` to `buf[len - 1]`.

The loop condition `i <= len` causes the loop to iterate from `i = 0` to `i = len` (inclusive). This means when `i == len`, the code executes `crc ^= buf[len]`. Since `buf` only contains valid indices `0` through `len-1`, accessing `buf[len]` results in an **out-of-bounds read**. Because this `buf` is allocated on the stack in `main`, the memory access at `buf[len]` reads the byte immediately following the array on the stack, triggering the stack buffer overflow/sanitizer error.

### Root-Cause Fix
The loop condition should be changed from `i <= len` (which allows iterating up to `len`) to `i < len` (which correctly iterates up to `len - 1`).

##### Recommendation

Change the loop condition in `program.c` at line 11.

